[ ] Add a canonical id and sort-key properties to the agenda qflist response contract and query =agenda-id-contract $ the qflist contract carries no stable identity, only source_file and source_line, and a line number moves the instant a file is edited, so it can navigate but cannot safely address a verb. bind the canonical IRI as the node id per query_output.md, and emit the ORDER BY keys as node properties so ordering survives an RDF round-trip $ !1 +core,cli #28ef6832-2c0c-4fac-82b8-56b8eeff4f03
[ ] Emit agenda output as JSON-LD conforming to query_output.md =agenda-jsonld-output $ SELECT stays the query form for an ordered list; frame the bindings into a single graph document with a node id, locator, display fields, and sort keys. one payload for the plugin and any integration partner, simple clients read the graph array and ignore the context $ !1 +core,cli <agenda-id-contract #cdb5b053-d4f2-4dfa-a8aa-bf89a28b8799
[ ] Make mutation verbs addressable by a bare id =verbs-by-id $ complete, update, and cancel must resolve a raw UUID directly with no fuzzy charter or alias resolution in the path, so a client holding a node id acts on exactly that node. this is the write half of the read, verb, reread loop $ !1 +cli <agenda-id-contract #87a4395a-1dea-4d10-a82c-ae0b2e5d8985
[ ] Return verb results as structured branchable data =verb-errors-as-data $ already-complete, not-found, and conflict come back as typed results rather than prose on stderr, so an automated loop or agent can respond rather than guess. this is what makes the save-gated automation controlled $ !2 +cli <verbs-by-id #ea929c08-fb94-4319-b3e5-d3a3a242739f
[ ] nvim maps JSON-LD nodes to quickfix entries =nvim-qflist-mapping $ the node id goes into the entry user_data as the invisible stable address, the locator into filename and lnum as the jump target, and the composed name, status, and due into the display text. the CLI never learns what quickfix is, this ten-line mapping is the plugin job $ !2 +nvim <agenda-jsonld-output #002abe33-96f3-4b35-9fec-d4e89b685a34
[ ] nvim closes the living loop =nvim-living-loop $ a keybind on the entry under cursor reads the id from user_data, fires the verb, reruns the query, and rebuilds the qflist. refresh is explicit and save-gated and the re-settle keeps the user in place. the same loop a human, an agent, or a future GUI would drive over the same primitives $ !2 +nvim <nvim-qflist-mapping <verbs-by-id #87528306-3e4c-4d94-9ad4-bf81fe6c67dc
